By the way, $TSLA traded consistently traded between $40-$60 in 15.  In 14, it traded in the $40's-$50's.  We could see that type of ramp-up here next year as EV's start to get hot.  I'd be shocked if this isn't trading in the 20's or 30's come spring time.

But investors aren't stupid.  Those who got into $TSLA early are rich right now and those who didn't, wish they did.  Do you honestly think people are going to be late to the boat here?  If Fisker can encapsulate even 1/10th of the EV market, it should trade well over $100/share

Now here's the kicker, in 2015, $TSLA sold 25,416 cars, so as you can see production can ramp up super quick.  If Fisker has a winner on his hands, you could see a few hundred thousand sold by 2025.  Another thing to consider; unless Elon slashes prices dramatically,

Just some perspective for long-term outlook on $SPAQ.  $TSLA has a market cap of 515x $SPAQ right now.  $TSLA sold 367,500 cars last year.  Fisker has 22k sold for the 2022.  Even if Tesla does 1 mil cars in 22, that's 515x market cap when revenues will likely only be 50x-75x.

6/ My $TSLA PT is $600, based on a 2025 EPS of $18 @ 50x P/E at 2024 YE, based on proj 2025-30 EPS growth of 25% (2x PEG). My 2024 YE price of $900 is disct’d at 9.5% for 4.25 years (Oct 2020 to Dec 2024). The 9.5% rate is 10yr Treas yld of 0.8%, plus 6% ERP x TSLA beta of 1.45x.

5/ $TSLA ‘s PT is the price at which an analyst expects TSLA to trade at in 6-12 mo.  Mathematically, it’s the PV of all dividends, plus the future price at which TSLA can trade in 5-10 years, discounted at the cost of equity, equal to the risk-free rate plus risk premium.

4/ $TSLA will rise if the market perceives TSLA delivery growth will accelerate, prices increase, or margins expand more than the market expects. Delivs are a function of global SAAR, EV penetration and TSLA’s EV share. Often the market anticipates a beat, then sells on the news.

3/ When a company like $TSLA beats earnings ests, it rises because future earnings often get revised upward, and P/Es can be repriced if markets assume the acceleration in growth persists. Non-recurring items (e.g., one time tax credits, legal settlements) are normally excluded.

To understand why $TSLA rises or falls, it’s best to use a present value (PV) framework.

PV is based on Yr1 EPS, growth over next n years, dividends, 10yr Treas yld, equity risk prem (ERP), beta, and a “steady state” P/E at which a stock trades n yrs out, based on future growth.
